# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: power-analysis-defense
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:power-analysis-defense/countermeasure-computer] In computer security a **countermeasure** is an action, device, procedure, or technique that reduces a threat, vulnerability, or attack, eliminating or preventing it by minimizing the harm it can cause.
[src:power-analysis-defense/countermeasure-computer] It can also include discovering and reporting vunerabilities so that corrective action can be taken.
[src:power-analysis-defense/countermeasure-computer] The definition is given in IETF RFC 2828 and CNSS Instruction No.
[src:power-analysis-defense/countermeasure-computer] 4009 dated 26 April 2010 by the Committee on National Security Systems.
[src:power-analysis-defense/countermeasure-computer] The deployment of a set of security services to protect against a security threat.
[src:power-analysis-defense/countermeasure-computer] In telecommunications, communication countermeasures are defined as security services as part of the OSI Reference model by ITU-T X.800 Recommendation.
[src:power-analysis-defense/countermeasure-computer] X.800 and ISO ISO 7498-2 (Information processing systems – Open systems interconnection – Basic Reference Model – Part 2: Security architecture are technically aligned.
[src:power-analysis-defense/countermeasure-computer] A resource (both physical or logical) can have one or more vulnerabilities that can be exploited by a threat agent in a threat action.
[src:power-analysis-defense/countermeasure-computer] The result can potentially compromise the confidentiality, integrity or availability properties of these resources (potentially different than the vulnerable one) of the organization and other involved parties (customers, suppliers).
[src:power-analysis-defense/countermeasure-computer] The so-called CIA triad is the basis of information security.
[src:power-analysis-defense/countermeasure-computer] The attack can be active when it attempts to alter system resources or affect their operation: so it compromises integrity or availability.
[src:power-analysis-defense/countermeasure-computer] A "passive attack" attempts to learn or make use of information from the system but does not affect system resources, compromising confidentiality.
[src:power-analysis-defense/countermeasure-computer] A threat is a potential for violation of security, which exists when there is a circumstance, capability, action, or event that could breach security and cause harm.
[src:power-analysis-defense/countermeasure-computer] That is, a threat is a possible danger enabling the exploitation of a vulnerability.
[src:power-analysis-defense/countermeasure-computer] A threat can be either "intentional" (i.e., intelligent; e.g., an individual cracker or a criminal organization) or "accidental" (e.g., the possibility of a computer malfunctioning, or the possibility of an "act of God" such as an earthquake, fire, or tornado).
[src:power-analysis-defense/countermeasure-computer] If a potential malicious actor has physical access to a computer system, they have a greater chance of inflicting harm upon it.
[src:power-analysis-defense/countermeasure-computer] Devices such as a USB Killer may be used to damage or render completely unusable anything with a connection to the motherboard of a computer, such as a USB port, video port, Ethernet port, or serial port.
[src:power-analysis-defense/countermeasure-computer] Without proper protection, these devices may result in the destruction of ports, adapter cards, storage devices, RAM, motherboards, CPUs, or anything physically connected to the device attacked, such as monitors, flash drives, or wired switches.
[src:power-analysis-defense/countermeasure-computer] These types of devices can even be used to damage smartphones and cars, as well.
[src:power-analysis-defense/countermeasure-computer] This threat can be mitigated by not installing or restricting physical access to easily accessible ports in situations where they are not necessary.
[src:power-analysis-defense/countermeasure-computer] A port-closing lock which permanently disables access to a port short of the actual port being disassembled.
[src:power-analysis-defense/countermeasure-computer] When it is necessary for a port to be accessible, an optocoupler can allow for a port to send and receive data to a computer or device without a direct electrical connection, preventing the computer or device from receiving any dangerous voltage from an external device.
[src:power-analysis-defense/countermeasure-computer] In an unsecured scenario, a malicious actor may steal or destroy storage devices such as hard drives or SSDs, resulting in the destruction or theft of valuable data.
[src:power-analysis-defense/countermeasure-computer] If the data of a storage device is no longer necessary, data theft is best prevented against by physically destroying or shredding the storage device.
[src:power-analysis-defense/countermeasure-computer] If the data of a storage device is in use and must be secured, one can use encryption to encrypt the contents of a storage device, or even encrypt the whole storage device save for the master boot record.
[src:power-analysis-defense/countermeasure-computer] The device can then be unlocked with a password, biometric authentication, a physical dongle, a network interchange, a one-time password, or any combination thereof.
[src:power-analysis-defense/countermeasure-computer] If this device is a boot drive, however, it must be unencrypted in a pre-boot environment so the operating system can be accessed.
[src:power-analysis-defense/countermeasure-computer] Not to be neglected is the process of adding physical barriers to the storage devices themselves.
[src:power-analysis-defense/countermeasure-computer] Locked cases or physically hidden drives, with a limited number of personnel with knowledge and access to the keys or locations, may prove to be a good first line against physical theft.
[src:power-analysis-defense/cryptographic-primitive] When creating cryptographic systems, designers use cryptographic primitives as their most basic building blocks.
[src:power-analysis-defense/cryptographic-primitive] Because of this, cryptographic primitives are designed to do one very specific task in a precisely defined and highly reliable fashion.
[src:power-analysis-defense/cryptographic-primitive] Since cryptographic primitives are used as building blocks, they must be very reliable, i.e. perform according to their specification.
[src:power-analysis-defense/cryptographic-primitive] For example, if an encryption routine claims to be only breakable with *X* number of computer operations, and it is broken with significantly fewer than *X* operations, then that cryptographic primitive has failed.
[src:power-analysis-defense/cryptographic-primitive] If a cryptographic primitive is found to fail, almost every protocol that uses it becomes vulnerable.
[src:power-analysis-defense/cryptographic-primitive] Since creating cryptographic routines is very hard, and testing them to be reliable takes a long time, it is essentially never sensible (nor secure) to design a new cryptographic primitive to suit the needs of a new cryptographic system.
[src:power-analysis-defense/cryptographic-primitive] Cryptographic primitives are one of the building blocks of every cryptosystem, e.g., TLS, SSL, SSH, etc.
[src:power-analysis-defense/cryptographic-primitive] Cryptosystem designers, not being in a position to definitively prove their security, must take the primitives they use as secure.
[src:power-analysis-defense/cryptographic-primitive] Choosing the best primitive available for use in a protocol usually provides the best available security.
[src:power-analysis-defense/cryptographic-primitive] However, compositional weaknesses are possible in any cryptosystem and it is the responsibility of the designer(s) to avoid them.
[src:power-analysis-defense/cryptographic-primitive] Cryptographic primitives are not cryptographic systems, as they are quite limited on their own.
[src:power-analysis-defense/cryptographic-primitive] For example, a bare encryption algorithm will provide no authentication mechanism, nor any explicit message integrity checking.
[src:power-analysis-defense/cryptographic-primitive] Only when combined in security protocols can more than one security requirement be addressed.
[src:power-analysis-defense/cryptographic-primitive] For example, to transmit a message that is not only encoded but also protected from tinkering (i.e. it is confidential and integrity-protected), an encoding routine, such as DES, and a hash-routine such as SHA-1 can be used in combination.
[src:power-analysis-defense/cryptographic-primitive] If the attacker does not know the encryption key, they cannot modify the message such that message digest value(s) would be valid.
[src:power-analysis-defense/cryptographic-primitive] Combining cryptographic primitives to make a security protocol is itself an entire specialization.
[src:power-analysis-defense/cryptographic-primitive] Most exploitable errors (i.e., insecurities in cryptosystems) are due not to design errors in the primitives (assuming always that they were chosen with care), but to the way they are used, i.e. bad protocol design and buggy or not careful enough implementation.
[src:power-analysis-defense/cryptographic-primitive] Mathematical analysis of protocols is, at the time of this writing, not mature.
[src:power-analysis-defense/cryptographic-primitive] There are some basic properties that can be verified with automated methods, such as BAN logic.
[src:power-analysis-defense/cryptographic-primitive] There are even methods for full verification (e.g. the SPI calculus) but they are extremely cumbersome and cannot be automated.
[src:power-analysis-defense/cryptographic-primitive] Protocol design is an art requiring deep knowledge and much practice; even then mistakes are common.
[src:power-analysis-defense/cryptographic-primitive] An illustrative example, for a real system, can be seen on the OpenSSL vulnerability news page here.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] In cryptography, a side channel attack is used to extract secret data from some secure device (such as a smart card, tamper-resistant "black box", or integrated circuit).
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] Side-channel analysis is typically trying to non-invasively extract cryptographic keys and other secret information from the device.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] A simple example of this is the German tank problem: the serial numbers of tanks provide details of the production data for tanks.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] In physical security, a non-invasive attack would be similar to lock-picking, where a successful attack leaves no trace of the attacker being present.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] Codeflow that depends on a secret value will thus leak the code-flow via the power consumption monitoring (and thus also leak the secret value).
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] This password check potentially contains a Timing attack, since the execution time is not constant.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] Observing the power consumption will make clear the number of loops executed.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] However, there is a mitigation possible.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] The function may not output to the user an exploitable result if, for example, there is a compensating delay before the response is returned.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] Or the code is structured to complete all the loops irrespective of the character position mismatching between the input and the secret-password.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] We can see one such sample code in the algorithm section of Timing attack.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] Similarly, squaring and multiplication operations in RSA implementations can often be distinguished, enabling an adversary to compute the secret key.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] Even if the magnitude of the variations in power consumption are small, standard digital oscilloscopes can easily show the data-induced variations.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] Frequency filters and averaging functions (such as those built into oscilloscopes) are often used to filter out high-frequency components.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] Power analysis provides a way to "see inside" otherwise 'tamperproof' hardware.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] For example, DES's key schedule involves rotating 28-bit key registers.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] Many implementations check the least significant bit to see if it is a 1.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] If so, the device shifts the register right and prepends the 1 at the left end.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] If the bit is a zero, the register is shifted right without prepending a 1.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] Power analysis can distinguish between these processes, enabling an adversary to determine the bits of the secret key.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] Implementations of algorithms such as AES and triple DES that are believed to be mathematically strong may be trivially breakable using power analysis attacks.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] As a result, power analysis attacks combine elements of algorithmic cryptanalysis and implementation security.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] For applications where devices may fall into the physical possession of an adversary, protection against power analysis is generally a major design requirement.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] Power analyses have also been reportedly used against conditional access modules used in pay television systems.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] The equipment necessary for performing power analysis attacks is widely available.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] For example, most digital storage oscilloscopes provide the necessary data collection functionality, and the data analysis is typically performed using conventional PCs.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] Power analysis attacks cannot generally be detected by a device, since the adversary's monitoring is normally passive.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] In addition, the attack is non-invasive.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] As a result, physical enclosures, auditing capabilities, and attack detectors are ineffective.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] Instead, cryptosystem engineers must ensure that devices' power variations do not reveal information usable by adversaries.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] Simple power analysis can easily distinguish the outcome of conditional branches in the execution of cryptographic software, since a device does different things (consuming different power) depending on whether the conditional branch is taken.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] For this reason, care should be taken to ensure there are no secret values which affect the conditional branches within cryptographic software implementations.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] Other sources of variation, such as microcode differences, branches introduced by compilers, and power consumption variations in multipliers, also commonly lead to SPA vulnerabilities.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] Differential power analysis is more difficult to prevent, since even small biases in the power consumption can lead to exploitable weaknesses.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] Some countermeasure strategies involve algorithmic modifications such that the cryptographic operations occur on data that is related to the actual value by some mathematical relationship that survives the cryptographic operation.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] One approach involves blinding parameters to randomize their value.
[src:power-analysis-defense/power-analysis] Other countermeasure strategies to reduce the effectiveness of DPA attacks involve hardware modifications: varying the chip internal clock frequency has been considered to desynchronize electric signals, which lead in return to algorithmic enhancements of traditional DPA.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] In computer security, a **side-channel attack** is a type of security exploit that uses information inadvertently leaked by a system—such as timing, power consumption, or electromagnetic or acoustic emissions—to gain unauthorized access to sensitive information.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] These attacks differ from those targeting flaws in the design of cryptographic protocols or algorithms (notwithstanding the fact that cryptanalysis may identify vulnerabilities relevant to both types of attacks).
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] Some side-channel attacks require technical knowledge of the internal operation of the system, others such as differential power analysis are effective as black-box attacks.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] Attempts to break a cryptosystem by deceiving or coercing people with legitimate access are not typically considered side-channel attacks: see social engineering and rubber-hose cryptanalysis.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] In all cases, the underlying principle is that physical effects caused by the operation of a cryptosystem (*on the side*) can provide useful extra information about secrets in the system, for example, the cryptographic key, partial state information, full or partial plaintexts and so forth.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] The term cryptophthora (secret degradation) is sometimes used to express the degradation of secret key material resulting from side-channel leakage.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] A **cache side-channel attack** works by monitoring security critical operations such as AES T-table entry or modular exponentiation or multiplication or memory accesses.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] The attacker then is able to recover the secret key depending on the accesses made (or not made) by the victim, deducing the encryption key.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] Also, unlike some of the other side-channel attacks, this method does not create a fault in the ongoing cryptographic operation and is invisible to the victim.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] In 2017, two CPU vulnerabilities (dubbed Meltdown and Spectre) were discovered, which can use a cache-based side channel to allow an attacker to leak memory contents of other processes and the operating system itself.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] A *power analysis* attack can provide even more detailed information by observing the power consumption of a hardware device such as CPU or cryptographic circuit.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] These attacks are roughly categorized into simple power analysis (SPA) and differential power analysis (DPA).
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] One example is Collide+Power, which affects nearly all CPUs.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] Other examples use machine learning approaches.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] Fluctuations in current also generate radio waves, enabling attacks that analyze measurements of electromagnetic (EM) emanations.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] These attacks typically involve similar statistical techniques as power-analysis attacks.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] A *deep-learning-based side-channel attack*, using the power and EM information across multiple devices has been demonstrated with the potential to break the secret key of a different but identical device in as low as a single trace.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] Historical analogues to modern side-channel attacks are known.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] A recently declassified NSA document reveals that as far back as 1943, an engineer with Bell telephone observed decipherable spikes on an oscilloscope associated with the decrypted output of a certain encrypting teletype.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] According to former MI5 officer Peter Wright, the British Security Service analyzed emissions from French cipher equipment in the 1960s.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] In the 1980s, Soviet eavesdroppers were suspected of having planted bugs inside IBM Selectric typewriters to monitor the electrical noise generated as the type ball rotated and pitched to strike the paper; the characteristics of those signals could determine which key was pressed.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] Power consumption of devices causes heating, which is offset by cooling effects.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] Temperature changes create thermally induced mechanical stress.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] This stress can create low level acoustic emissions from operating CPUs (about 10 kHz in some cases).
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] Recent research by Shamir et al. has suggested that information about the operation of cryptosystems and algorithms can be obtained in this way as well.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] This is an *acoustic cryptanalysis attack*.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] If the surface of the CPU chip, or in some cases the CPU package, can be observed, infrared images can also provide information about the code being executed on the CPU, known as a *thermal-imaging attack*.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] An *optical side-channel attack* examples include gleaning information from the hard disk activity indicator to reading a small number of photons emitted by transistors as they change state.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] Under the first category, displays with special shielding to lessen electromagnetic emissions, reducing susceptibility to TEMPEST attacks, are now commercially available.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] Power line conditioning and filtering can help deter power-monitoring attacks, although such measures must be used cautiously, since even very small correlations can remain and compromise security.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] Physical enclosures can reduce the risk of surreptitious installation of microphones (to counter acoustic attacks) and other micro-monitoring devices (against CPU power-draw or thermal-imaging attacks).
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] Another countermeasure (still in the first category) is to jam the emitted channel with noise.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] For instance, a random delay can be added to deter timing attacks, although adversaries can compensate for these delays by averaging multiple measurements (or, more generally, using more measurements in the analysis).
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] When the amount of noise in the side channel increases, the adversary needs to collect more measurements.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] Another countermeasure under the first category is to use security analysis software to identify certain classes of side-channel attacks that can be found during the design stages of the underlying hardware itself.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] Timing attacks and cache attacks are both identifiable through certain commercially available security analysis software platforms, which allow for testing to identify the attack vulnerability itself, as well as the effectiveness of the architectural change to circumvent the vulnerability.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] The most comprehensive method to employ this countermeasure is to create a Secure Development Lifecycle for hardware, which includes utilizing all available security analysis platforms at their respective stages of the hardware development lifecycle.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] In the case of timing attacks against targets whose computation times are quantized into discrete clock cycle counts, an effective countermeasure against is to design the software to be isochronous, that is to run in an exactly constant amount of time, independently of secret values.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] Such countermeasures can be difficult to implement in practice, since even individual instructions can have variable timing on some CPUs.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] One partial countermeasure against simple power attacks, but not differential power-analysis attacks, is to design the software so that it is "PC-secure" in the "program counter security model".
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] In a PC-secure program, the execution path does not depend on secret values.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] In other words, all conditional branches depend only on public information.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] On architectures where the instruction execution time is not data-dependent, a PC-secure program is also immune to timing attacks.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] Another way in which code can be non-isochronous is that modern CPUs have a memory cache: accessing infrequently used information incurs a large timing penalty, revealing some information about the frequency of use of memory blocks.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] Cryptographic code designed to resist cache attacks attempts to use memory in only a predictable fashion (like accessing only the input, outputs and program data, and doing so according to a fixed pattern).
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] For example, data-dependent table lookups must be avoided because the cache could reveal which part of the lookup table was accessed.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] Other partial countermeasures attempt to reduce the amount of information leaked from data-dependent power differences.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] Some operations use power that is correlated to the number of 1 bits in a secret value.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] Using a constant-weight code (such as using Fredkin gates or dual-rail encoding) can reduce the leakage of information about the Hamming weight of the secret value, although exploitable correlations are likely to remain unless the balancing is perfect.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] This "balanced design" can be approximated in software by manipulating both the data and its complement together.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] Several "secure CPUs" have been built as asynchronous CPUs; they have no global timing reference.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] While these CPUs were intended to make timing and power attacks more difficult, subsequent research found that timing variations in asynchronous circuits are harder to remove.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] Recently, white-box modeling was utilized to develop a low-overhead generic circuit-level countermeasure against both EM as well as power side-channel attacks.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] To minimize the effects of the higher-level metal layers in an IC acting as more efficient antennas, the idea is to embed the crypto core with a signature suppression circuit, routed locally within the lower-level metal layers, leading towards both power and EM side-channel attack immunity.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] As a countermeasure for message encryption, **masking** (also known as **blinding**) is effective against all side-channel attacks.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] The principle of masking is to avoid manipulating any sensitive value y directly, but rather manipulate a sharing of it: a set of variables (called "shares") $y_{1},...,y_{d}$ such that $y=y_{1}\oplus ...\oplus y_{d}$ (where $\oplus$ is the XOR operation).
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] An attacker must recover all the values of the shares to get any meaningful information.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] Since the decrypting system chose r , it can compute its inverse modulo m to cancel out the factor r in the result and obtain $y^{d}$ , the actual result of the decryption.
[src:power-analysis-defense/side-channel-attack] For attacks that require collecting side-channel information from operations with data *controlled by the attacker*, blinding is an effective countermeasure, since the actual operation is executed on a randomized version of the data, over which the attacker has no control or even knowledge.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] A **smart card** (**SC**), **chip card**, or **integrated circuit card** (**ICC** or **IC card**), is a card used to control access to a resource.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] It is typically a plastic credit card-sized card with an embedded integrated circuit (IC) chip.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Many smart cards include a pattern of metal contacts to electrically connect to the internal chip.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Others are contactless, and some are both.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Smart cards can provide personal identification, authentication, data storage, and application processing.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Applications include identification, financial, public transit, computer security, schools, and healthcare.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Smart cards may provide strong security authentication for single sign-on (SSO) within organizations.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Numerous nations have deployed smart cards throughout their populations.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The universal integrated circuit card (UICC) for mobile phones, installed as pluggable SIM card or embedded eSIM, is also a type of smart card.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] As of 2015, 10.5 billion smart card IC chips are manufactured annually, including 5.44 billion SIM card IC chips.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The basis for the smart card is the silicon integrated circuit (IC) chip.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] It was invented by Robert Noyce at Fairchild Semiconductor in 1959.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The invention of the silicon integrated circuit led to the idea of incorporating it onto a plastic card in the late 1960s.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The idea of incorporating an integrated circuit chip onto a plastic card was first introduced by the German engineer Helmut Gröttrup.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] In February 1967, Gröttrup filed the patents DE1574074 and DE1574075 in West Germany for a tamper-proof identification switch based on a semiconductor device and described contactless communication via inductive coupling.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Its primary use was intended to provide individual copy-protected keys for releasing the tapping process at unmanned gas stations.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] In September 1968, Gröttrup, together with Jürgen Dethloff as an investor, filed further patents for this identification switch, first in Austria and in 1969 as subsequent applications in the United States, Great Britain, West Germany and other countries.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Independently, Kunitaka Arimura of the Arimura Technology Institute in Japan developed a similar idea of incorporating an integrated circuit onto a plastic card, and filed a smart card patent in March 1970.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The following year, Paul Castrucci of IBM filed an American patent titled "Information Card" in May 1971.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] In 1974 Roland Moreno patented a secured memory card later dubbed the "smart card".
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] In 1976, Jürgen Dethloff introduced the known element (called "the secret") to identify gate user as of USP 4105156.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] In 1977, Michel Ugon from Honeywell Bull invented the first microprocessor smart card with two chips: one microprocessor and one memory, and in 1978, he patented the self-programmable one-chip microcomputer (SPOM) that defines the necessary architecture to program the chip.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Three years later, Motorola used this patent in its "CP8".
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] At that time, Bull had 1,200 patents related to smart cards.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] In 2001, Bull sold its CP8 division together with its patents to Schlumberger, who subsequently combined its own internal smart card department and CP8 to create Axalto.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] In 2006, Axalto and Gemplus, at the time the world's top two smart-card manufacturers, merged and became Gemalto.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] In 2008, Dexa Systems spun off from Schlumberger and acquired Enterprise Security Services business, which included the smart-card solutions division responsible for deploying the first large-scale smart-card management systems based on public key infrastructure (PKI).
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The first mass use of the cards was as a telephone card for payment in French payphones, starting in 1983.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] After the Télécarte, microchips were integrated into all French *Carte Bleue* debit cards in 1992.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Customers inserted the card into the merchant's point-of-sale (POS) terminal, then typed the personal identification number (PIN), before the transaction was accepted.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Only very limited transactions (such as paying small highway tolls) are processed without a PIN.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Smart-card-based "electronic purse" systems store funds on the card, so that readers do not need network connectivity.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] They entered European service in the mid-1990s.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Private electronic purse systems have also been deployed such as the Marines corps (USMC) at Parris Island allowing small amount payments at the cafeteria.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Since the 1990s, smart cards have been the subscriber identity modules (SIMs) used in GSM mobile-phone equipment.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Mobile phones are widely used across the world, so smart cards have become very common.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Europay MasterCard Visa (EMV)-compliant cards and equipment are widespread with the deployment led by European countries.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The United States started later deploying the EMV technology in 2014, with the deployment still in progress in 2019.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Typically, a country's national payment association, in coordination with MasterCard International, Visa International, American Express and Japan Credit Bureau (JCB), jointly plan and implement EMV systems.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Historically, in 1993 several international payment companies agreed to develop smart-card specifications for debit and credit cards.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The original brands were MasterCard, Visa, and Europay.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The first version of the EMV system was released in 1994.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] In 1998 the specifications became stable.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] EMVco's purpose is to assure the various financial institutions and retailers that the specifications retain backward compatibility with the 1998 version.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] EMVco upgraded the specifications in 2000 and 2004.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] EMV compliant cards were first accepted into Malaysia in 2005 and later into United States in 2014.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] MasterCard was the first company that was allowed to use the technology in the United States.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The United States has felt pushed to use the technology because of the increase in identity theft.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The credit card information stolen from Target in late 2013 was one of the largest indicators that American credit card information is not safe.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Target made the decision on 30 April 2014 that it would try to implement the smart chip technology to protect itself from future credit card identity theft.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Before 2014, the consensus in America was that there were enough security measures to avoid credit card theft and that the smart chip was not necessary.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The cost of the smart chip technology was significant, which was why most of the corporations did not want to pay for it in the United States.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The debate finally ended when Target sent out a notice stating unauthorized access to magnetic strips costing Target over 300 million dollars along with the increasing cost of online credit theft was enough for the United States to invest in the technology.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The adaptation of EMV's increased significantly in 2015 when the liability shifts occurred in October by the credit card companies.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Use of "Contactless" smart cards in transport has also grown through the use of low cost chips NXP Mifare Ultralight and paper/card/PET rather than PVC.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] This has reduced media cost so it can be used for low cost tickets and short term transport passes (up to 1 year typically).
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The cost is typically 10% that of a PVC smart card with larger memory.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] They are distributed through vending machines, ticket offices and agents.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Use of paper/PET is less harmful to the environment than traditional PVC cards.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Smart cards are also being introduced for identification and entitlement by regional, national, and international organizations.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] These uses include citizen cards, drivers’ licenses, and patient cards.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] In Malaysia, the compulsory national ID MyKad enables eight applications and has 18 million users.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Contactless smart cards are part of ICAO biometric passports to enhance security for international travel.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Complex Cards are smart cards that conform to the ISO/IEC 7810 standard and include components in addition to those found in traditional single chip smart cards.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Complex Cards were invented by Cyril Lalo and Philippe Guillaud in 1999 when they designed a chip smart card with additional components, building upon the initial concept consisting of using audio frequencies to transmit data patented by Alain Bernard.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The first Complex Card prototype was developed collaboratively by Cyril Lalo and Philippe Guillaud, who were working at AudioSmartCard at the time, and Henri Boccia and Philippe Patrice, who were working at Gemplus.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] It was ISO 7810-compliant and included a battery, a piezoelectric buzzer, a button, and delivered audio functions, all within a 0.84mm thickness card.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The Complex Card pilot, developed by AudioSmartCard, was launched in 2002 by Crédit Lyonnais, a French financial institution.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] This pilot featured acoustic tones as a means of authentication.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Although Complex Cards were developed since the inception of the smart card industry, they only reached maturity after 2010.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] While first generation Complex Cards were battery powered, the second generation is battery-free and receives power through the usual card connector and/or induction .
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Sound, generated by a buzzer, was the preferred means of communication for the first projects involving Complex Cards.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Later, with the progress of displays, visual communication is now present in almost all Complex Cards.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Complex Cards support all communication protocols present on regular smart cards: contact, thanks to a contact pad as defined ISO/IEC 7816 standard, contactless following the ISO/IEC 14443 standard, and magstripe.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] A Complex Card can be used to compute a cryptographic value, such as a One-time password.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The One-Time Password is generated by a cryptoprocessor encapsulated in the card.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] To implement this function, the crypto processor must be initialized with a seed value, which enables the identification of the OTPs respective of each card.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The hash of seed value has to be stored securely within the card to prevent unauthorized prediction of the generated OTPs.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] One-Time Passwords generation is based either on incremental values (event based) or on a real time clock (time based).
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Using clock-based One-Time Password generation requires the Complex Card to be equipped with a Real-time clock.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] A Complex Card with buttons can display the balance of one or multiple account(s) linked to the card.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Typically, either one button is used to display the balance in the case of a single account card or, in the case of a card linked to multiple accounts, a combination of buttons is used to select a specific account's balance.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] For additional security, features such as requiring the user to enter an identification or a security value such as a PIN can be added to a Complex Card.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The latest generation of battery free, button free, Complex Cards can display a balance or other kind of information without requiring any input from the card holder.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The information is updated during the use of the card.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] For instance, in a transit card, key information such as the monetary value balance, the number of remaining trips or the expiry date of a transit pass can be displayed.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] A Complex Card being deployed as a payment card can be equipped with capability to provide transaction security.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Typically, online payments are made secure thanks to the Card Security Code (CSC), also known as card verification code (CVC2), or card verification value (CVV2).
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The card security code (CSC) is a 3 or 4 digits number printed on a credit or debit card, used as a security feature for card-not-present (CNP) payment card transactions to reduce the incidence of fraud.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The Card Security Code (CSC) is to be given to the merchant by the cardholder to complete a card-not-present transaction.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The CSC is transmitted along with other transaction data and verified by the card issuer.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) prohibits the storage of the CSC by the merchant or any stakeholder in the payment chain.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Although designed to be a security feature, the static CSC is susceptible to fraud as it can easily be memorized by a shop attendant, who could then use it for fraudulent online transactions or sale on the dark web.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] This vulnerability has led the industry to develop a Dynamic Card Security Code (DCSC) that can be changed at certain time intervals, or after each contact or contactless EMV transaction.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] This Dynamic CSC brings significantly better security than a static CSC.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The first generation of Dynamic CSC cards, developed by NagraID Security required a battery, a quartz and Real Time Clock (RTC) embedded within the card to power the computation of a new Dynamic CSC, after expiration of the programmed period.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The second generation of Dynamic CSC cards, developed by Ellipse World, Inc., does not require any battery, quartz, or RTC to compute and display the new dynamic code.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Instead, the card obtains its power either through the usual card connector or by induction during every EMV transaction from the Point of Sales (POS) terminal or Automated Teller Machine (ATM) to compute a new DCSC.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The advantage of the Dynamic Card Security Code (DCSC) is that new information is transmitted with the payment transactions, thus making it useless for a potential fraudster to memorize or store it.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] A transaction with a Dynamic Card Security Code is carried out exactly the same way, with the same processes and use of parameters as a transaction with a static code in a card-not-present transaction.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Upgrading to a DCSC allows cardholders and merchants to continue their payment habits and processes undisturbed.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Complex Cards can be equipped with biometric sensors allowing for stronger user authentication.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] In the typical use case, fingerprint sensors are integrated into a payment card to bring a higher level of user authentication than a PIN.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] To implement user authentication using a fingerprint enabled smart card, the user has to authenticate himself/herself to the card by means of the fingerprint before starting a payment transaction.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Complex Cards can incorporate a wide variety of components.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The choice of components drives functionality, influences cost, power supply needs, and manufacturing complexity.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Depending on Complex Card types, buttons have been added to allow an easy interaction between the user and the card.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] While separate keys have been used on prototypes in the early days, capacitive keyboards are the most popular solution now, thanks to technology developments by AudioSmartCard International SA.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The interaction with a capacitive keyboard requires constant power, therefore a battery and a mechanical button are required to activate the card.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The first Complex Cards were equipped with a buzzer that made it possible to broadcast sound.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] This feature was generally used over the phone to send identification data such as an identifier and one-time passwords (OTPs).
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Technologies used for sound transmission include DTMF (dual-tone multi-frequency signaling) or FSK (frequency-shift keying).
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Displaying data is an essential part of Complex Card functionalities.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Depending on the information that needs to be shown, displays can be digital or alphanumeric and of varying lengths.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Displays can be located either on the front or back of the card.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] A front display is the most common solution for showing information such as a One-Time Password or an electronic purse balance.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] A rear display is more often used for showing a Dynamic Card Security Code (DCSC).
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] If a Complex smart Card is dedicated to making cryptographic computations (such as generating a one-time password) it may require a secure cryptoprocessor.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] As Complex Cards contain more components than traditional smart cards, their power consumption must be carefully monitored.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] First generation Complex Cards require a power supply even in standby mode.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] As such, product designers generally included a battery in their design.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Incorporating a battery creates an additional burden in terms of complexity, cost, space and flexibility in an already dense design.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Including a battery in a Complex Card increases the complexity of the manufacturing process as a battery cannot be hot laminated.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Second generation Complex Cards feature a battery-free design.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] These cards harvest the necessary power from external sources; for example when the card interacts in a contact or contactless fashion with a payment system or an NFC-enabled smartphone.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The use of a bistable display in the card design ensures that the screen remains legible even when the Complex Card is unconnected to the power source.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Complex Card manufacturing methods are inherited from the smart card industry and from the electronics mounting industry.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] As Complex Cards incorporate several components while having to remain within 0.8 mm thickness and be flexible, and to comply with the ISO/IEC 7810, ISO/IEC 7811 and ISO/IEC 7816 standards, renders their manufacture more complex than standard smart cards.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] One of the most popular manufacturing processes in the smart card industry is lamination.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] This process involves laminating an inlay between two card faces.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The inlay contains the needed electronic components with an antenna printed on an inert support.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Typically battery-powered Complex Cards require a cold lamination manufacturing process.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] This process impacts the manufacturing lead time and the whole cost of such a Complex Card.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Second generation, battery-free Complex Cards can be manufactured by existing hot lamination process.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] This automated process, inherited from traditional smart card manufacturing, enables the production of Complex Cards in large quantities while keeping costs under control, a necessity for the evolution from a niche to a mass market.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] As Complex Cards bring more functionalities than standard smart cards and, due to their complexity, their personalization can take longer or require more inputs.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Having Complex Cards that can be personalized by the same machines and the same processes as regular smart cards allows them to be integrated more easily in existing manufacturing chains and applications.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] First generation, battery-operated Complex Cards require specific recycling processes, mandated by different regulatory bodies.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Additionally, keeping battery-operated Complex Cards in inventory for extended periods of time may reduce their performance due to battery ageing.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Second-generation battery-free technology ensures operation during the entire lifetime of the card and eliminates self-discharge, providing extended shelf life, and is more eco-friendly.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Since the inception of smart cards, innovators have been trying to add extra features.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] As technologies have matured and have been industrialized, several smart card industry players have been involved in Complex Cards.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The Complex Card concept began in 1999 when Cyril Lalo and Philippe Guillaud, its inventors, first designed a smart card with additional components.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The first prototype was developed collaboratively by Cyril Lalo, who was the CEO of AudioSmartCard at the time, and Henri Boccia and Philippe Patrice, from Gemplus.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The prototype included a button and audio functions on a 0.84mm thick ISO 7810-compliant card .
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Since then, Complex Cards have been mass-deployed primarily by NagraID Security.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] AudioSmartCard International SA was instrumental in developing the first Complex Card that included a battery, a piezoelectric buzzer, a button, and audio functions all on a 0.84mm thick, ISO 7810-compatible card.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] AudioSmartCard was founded in 1993 and specialized in the development and marketing of acoustic tokens incorporating security features.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] These acoustic tokens exchanged data in the form of sounds transmitted over a phone line.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] In 1999, AudioSmartCard transitioned to a new leadership under Cyril Lalo and Philippe Guillaud, who also became major shareholders.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] They made AudioSmartCard evolve towards the smart card world.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] In 2003 Prosodie, a subsidiary of Capgemini, joined the shareholders of AudioSmartCard.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] AudioSmartCard was renamed nCryptone, in 2004.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] CardLab Innovation, incorporated in 2006 in Herlev, Denmark, specializes in Complex Cards that include a switch, a biometric reader, an RFID jammer, and one or more magstripes.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The company works with manufacturing partners in China and Thailand and owns a card lamination factory in Thailand.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Coin was a US-based startup founded in 2012 by Kanishk Parashar.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] It developed a Complex Card capable of storing the data of several credit and debit cards.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The card prototype was equipped with a display and a button that enabled the user to switch between different cards.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] In 2015, the original Coin card concept evolved into Coin 2.0 adding contactless communication to its original magstripe emulation.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Coin was acquired by Fitbit in May 2016 and all Coin activities were discontinued in February 2017.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Ellipse World, Inc. was founded in 2017 by Cyril Lalo and Sébastien Pochic, both recognized experts in Complex Card technology.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Ellipse World, Inc. specializes in battery-free Complex Card technology.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The Ellipse patented technologies enable smart card manufacturers to use their existing dual interface payment card manufacturing process and supply chain to build battery-free, second generation Complex Cards with display capabilities.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Thanks to this ease of integration, smart card vendors are able to address banking, transit and prepaid cards markets.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] EMue Technologies, headquartered in Melbourne, Australia, designed and developed authentication solutions for the financial services industry from 2009 to 2015.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The company's flagship product, developed in collaboration with Cyril Lalo and Philippe Guillaud, was the eMue Card, a Visa CodeSure credit card with an embedded keypad, a display and a microprocessor.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Feitian Technologies, a China-based company created in 1998, provides cyber security products and solutions.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The company offers security solutions based on smart cards as well as other authentication devices.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] These include Complex Cards, that incorporate a display, a keypad or a fingerprint sensor.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Fingerprint Cards AB (or Fingerprints) is a Swedish company specializing in biometric solutions.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The company sells biometric sensors and has recently introduced payment cards incorporating a fingerprint sensor such as the Zwipe card, a biometric dual-interface payment card using an integrated sensor from Fingerprints.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Giesecke & Devrient, also known as G+D, is a German company headquartered in Munich that provides banknotes, security printing, smart cards and cash handling systems.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Its smart card portfolio includes display cards, OTP cards, as well as cards displaying a Dynamic CSC.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Gemalto, a division of Thales Group, is a major player in the secure transaction industry.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The company's Complex Card portfolio includes cards with a display or a fingerprint sensor.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] These cards may display an OTP or a Dynamic CSC.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] IDEMIA is the product of the 2017 merger of Oberthur Technologies and Morpho.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The combined company has positioned itself as a global provider of financial cards, SIM cards, biometric devices as well as public and private identity solutions.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Due to Oberthur's acquisition of NagraID Security in 2014, Idemia's Complex Card offerings include the F.CODE biometric payment card that includes a fingerprint sensor, and its battery-powered Motion Code card that displays a Dynamic CSC.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] IDEX Biometrics ASA, incorporated in Norway, specializes in fingerprint identification technologies for personal authentication.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The company offers fingerprint sensors and modules that are ready to be embedded into cards.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Founded in 2002, by Alan Finkelstein, Innovative Card Technologies developed and commercialized enhancements for the smart card market.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The company acquired the display card assets of nCryptone in 2006.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Innovative Card Technologies has ceased its activities.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Nagra ID, now known as NID, was a wholly owned subsidiary of the Kudelski Group until 2014.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] NID can trace its history with Complex Cards back to 2003 when it collaborated on development with nCryptone.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Nagra ID was instrumental in developing the cold lamination process for Complex Cards manufacturing.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Nagra ID manufactures Complex Cards that can include a battery, buttons, displays or other electronic components.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Nagra ID Security began in 2008 as a spinoff of Nagra ID to focus on Complex Card development and manufacturing.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The company was owned by Kudelski Group (50%), Cyril Lalo (25%) and Philippe Guillaud (25%).
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] NagraID Security quickly became a leading player in the adoption of Complex Cards due, in large part, to its development of MotionCode cards that featured a small display to enable a Card Security Code (CVV2).
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] NagraID Security was the first Complex Cards manufacturer to develop a mass market for payment display cards.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] In 2014, NagraID Security was sold to Oberthur Technologies (now IDEMIA).
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] nCryptone emerged in 2004 from the renaming of AudioSmartCard. nCryptone was headed by Cyril Lalo and Philippe Guillaud and developed technologies around authentication servers and devices.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] nCryptone display card assets were acquired by Innovative Card Technologies in 2006.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Oberthur Technologies, now IDEMIA, is one of the major players in the secure transactions industry.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] It acquired the business of NagraID Security in 2014.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Oberthur then merged with Morpho and the combined entity was renamed Idemia in 2017.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Set up in 2009, Plastc announced a single card that could digitally hold the data of up to 20 credit or debit cards.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The company succeeded in raising US$9 million through preorders but failed to deliver any product.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Plastc was then acquired in 2017 by Edge Mobile Payments, a Santa Cruz-based Fintech company.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The Plastc project continues as the Edge card, a dynamic payment card that consolidates several payment cards in one device.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The card is equipped with a battery and an ePaper screen and can store data from up to 50 credit, debit, loyalty and gift cards.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Stratos was created in 2012 in Ann Arbor, Michigan, USA.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] In 2015, Stratos developed the Stratos Bluetooth Connected Card, which was designed to integrate up to three credit and debit card in a single card format and featured a smartphone app used to manage the card.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Due to its Lithium ion thin film battery, the Stratos card was equipped with LEDs and communicated in contactless mode and in Bluetooth low Energy.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] In 2017 Stratos was acquired by CardLab Innovation, a company headquartered in Herlev, Denmark.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] SWYP was the brand name of a card developed by Qvivr, a company incorporated in 2014 in Fremont, California.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] SWYP was introduced in 2015 and dubbed the world's first smart wallet.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] SWYP was a metal card with the ability to combine over 25 credit, debit, gift and loyalty cards.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The card worked in conjunction with a smartphone app used to manage the cards.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The Swyp card included a battery, a button and a matrix display that showed which card was in use.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The company registered users in its beta testing program, but the product never shipped on a commercial scale.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Qvivr raised US$5 million in January 2017 and went out of business in November 2017.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Complex Cards have been adopted by numerous financial institutions worldwide.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] They may include different functionalities such as payment cards (credit, debit, prepaid), One-time password, mass-transit, and dynamic Card Security Code (CVV2).
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Since April 2009, a Japanese company has manufactured reusable financial smart cards made from paper.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] As mentioned above, data on a smart card may be stored in a file system (FS).
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] In smart card file systems, the root directory is called the "master file" ("MF"), subdirectories are called "dedicated files" ("DF"), and ordinary files are called "elementary files" ("EF").
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The file system mentioned above is stored on an EEPROM (storage or memory) within the smartcard.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] In addition to the EEPROM, other components may be present, depending upon the kind of smartcard.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] In cards with microprocessors, the microprocessor sits inline between the reader and the other components.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The operating system that runs on the microprocessor mediates the reader's access to those components to prevent unauthorized access.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Contact smart cards have a contact area of approximately 1 square centimetre (0.16 sq in), comprising several gold-plated contact pads.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] These pads provide electrical connectivity when inserted into a reader, which is used as a communications medium between the smart card and a host (e.g., a computer, a point of sale terminal) or a mobile telephone.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Cards do not contain batteries; power is supplied by the card reader.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Because the chips in financial cards are the same as those used in subscriber identity modules (SIMs) in mobile phones, programmed differently and embedded in a different piece of PVC, chip manufacturers are building to the more demanding GSM/3G standards.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] So, for example, although the EMV standard allows a chip card to draw 50 mA from its terminal, cards are normally well below the telephone industry's 6 mA limit.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] This allows smaller and cheaper financial card terminals.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Communication protocols for contact smart cards include T=0 (character-level transmission protocol, defined in ISO/IEC 7816-3) and T=1 (block-level transmission protocol, defined in ISO/IEC 7816-3).
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] APDU transmission by a contactless interface is defined in ISO/IEC 14443-4.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Hybrid cards implement contactless and contact interfaces on a single card with unconnected chips including dedicated modules/storage and processing.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Dual-interface cards implement contactless and contact interfaces on a single chip with some shared storage and processing.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] An example is Porto's multi-application transport card, called Andante, which uses a chip with both contact and contactless (ISO/IEC 14443 Type B) interfaces.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Numerous payment cards worldwide are based on hybrid card technology allowing them to communicate in contactless as well as contact modes.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] The CCID (Chip Card Interface Device) is a USB protocol that allows a smart card to be interfaced to a computer using a card reader which has a standard USB interface.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] This allows the smart card to be used as a security token for authentication and data encryption such as Bitlocker.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] A typical CCID is a USB dongle and may contain a SIM.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Different smart cards implement one or more reader-side protocols.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Common protocols here include CT-API and PC/SC.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Smartcard operating systems may provide application programming interfaces (APIs) so that developers can write programs ("applications") to run on the smartcard.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p01] Some such APIs, such as Java Card, allow programs to be uploaded to the card without replacing the card's entire operating system.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Smart cards serve as credit or ATM cards, fuel cards, mobile phone SIMs, authorization cards for pay television, household utility pre-payment cards, high-security identification and access badges, and public transport and public phone payment cards.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Smart cards may also be used as electronic wallets.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] The smart card chip can be "loaded" with funds to pay parking meters, vending machines or merchants.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Cryptographic protocols protect the exchange of money between the smart card and the machine.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] The holder of the card may use it even if not the owner.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Examples are Mondex (1993), Proton, Geldkarte, Chipknip and Moneo.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] The German Geldkarte is also used to validate customer age at vending machines for cigarettes.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Contactless (non-PIN) transactions cover a payment range of ~$5–50.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] There is an ISO/IEC 14443 PayPass implementation.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Some, but not all, PayPass implementations conform to EMV.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Non-EMV cards work like magnetic stripe cards.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] The cards do not hold or maintain the account balance.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] All payment passes without a PIN, usually in off-line mode.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] The security of such a transaction is no greater than with a magnetic stripe card transaction.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] EMV cards can have either contact or contactless interfaces.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] They work as if they were a normal EMV card with a contact interface.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Via the contactless interface they work somewhat differently, in that the card commands enabled improved features such as lower power and shorter transaction times.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] EMV standards include provisions for contact and contactless communications.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Typically modern payment cards are based on hybrid card technology and support both contact and contactless communication modes.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] The subscriber identity modules used in mobile-phone systems are reduced-size smart cards, using otherwise identical technologies.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Sometimes they employ a public key infrastructure (PKI).
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] The card stores an encrypted digital certificate issued from the PKI provider along with other relevant information.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Department of Defense (DoD) Common Access Card (CAC), and other cards used by other governments for their citizens.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] If they include biometric identification data, cards can provide superior two- or three-factor authentication.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Smart cards are not always privacy-enhancing, because the subject may carry incriminating information on the card.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Contactless smart cards that can be read from within a wallet or even a garment simplify authentication; however, criminals may access data from these cards.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Cryptographic smart cards are often used for single sign-on.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Most advanced smart cards include specialized cryptographic hardware that uses algorithms such as RSA and Digital Signature Algorithm (DSA).
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Today's cryptographic smart cards generate key pairs on board, to avoid the risk from having more than one copy of the key (since by design there usually isn't a way to extract private keys from a smart card).
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Such smart cards are mainly used for digital signatures and secure identification.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] The most common way to access cryptographic smart card functions on a computer is to use a vendor-provided PKCS#11 library.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] On Microsoft Windows the Cryptographic Service Provider (CSP) API is also supported.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] The most widely used cryptographic algorithms in smart cards (excluding the GSM so-called "crypto algorithm") are Triple DES and RSA.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] The key set is usually loaded (DES) or generated (RSA) on the card at the personalization stage.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Some of these smart cards are also made to support the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) standard for Personal Identity Verification, FIPS 201.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Turkey implemented the first smart card driver's license system in 1987.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Turkey had a high level of road accidents and decided to develop and use digital tachograph devices on heavy vehicles, instead of the existing mechanical ones, to reduce speed violations.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Since 1987, the professional driver's licenses in Turkey have been issued as smart cards.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] A professional driver is required to insert his driver's license into a digital tachograph before starting to drive.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] The tachograph unit records speed violations for each driver and gives a printed report.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] The driving hours for each driver are also being monitored and reported.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] In 1990 the European Union conducted a feasibility study through BEVAC Consulting Engineers, titled "Feasibility study with respect to a European electronic drivers license (based on a smart-card) on behalf of Directorate General VII".
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] In this study, chapter seven describes Turkey's experience.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Argentina's Mendoza province began using smart card driver's licenses in 1995.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Mendoza also had a high level of road accidents, driving offenses, and a poor record of recovering fines.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Smart licenses hold up-to-date records of driving offenses and unpaid fines.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] They also store personal information, license type and number, and a photograph.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Emergency medical information such as blood type, allergies, and biometrics (fingerprints) can be stored on the chip if the card holder wishes.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] The Argentina government anticipates that this system will help to collect more than $10 million per year in fines.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] In 1999 Gujarat was the first Indian state to introduce a smart card license system.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] As of 2005, it has issued 5 million smart card driving licenses to its people.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] In 2002, the Estonian government started to issue smart cards named ID Kaart as primary identification for citizens to replace the usual passport in domestic and EU use.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] As of 2010 about 1 million smart cards have been issued (total population is about 1.3 million) and they are widely used in internet banking, buying public transport tickets, authorization on various websites etc.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] By the start of 2009, the entire population of Belgium was issued eID cards that are used for identification.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] These cards contain two certificates: one for authentication and one for signature.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] More and more services in Belgium use eID for authorization.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Spain started issuing national ID cards (DNI) in the form of smart cards in 2006 and gradually replaced all the older ones with smart cards.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] The idea was that many or most bureaucratic acts could be done online but it was a failure because the Administration did not adapt and still mostly requires paper documents and personal presence.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] On 14 August 2012, the ID cards in Pakistan were replaced.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] The Smart Card is a third generation chip-based identity document that is produced according to international standards and requirements.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] The card has over 36 physical security features and has the latest encryption codes.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] This smart card replaced the NICOP (the ID card for overseas Pakistani).
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Smart cards may identify emergency responders and their skills.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Cards like these allow first responders to bypass organizational paperwork and focus more time on the emergency resolution.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] WidePoint Corporation, a smart card provider to FEMA, produces cards that contain additional personal information, such as medical records and skill sets.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] In 2007, the Open Mobile Alliance (OMA) proposed a new standard defining V1.0 of the Smart Card Web Server (SCWS), an HTTP server embedded in a SIM card intended for a smartphone user.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] The non-profit trade association SIMalliance has been promoting the development and adoption of SCWS.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] SIMalliance states that SCWS offers end-users a familiar, OS-independent, browser-based interface to secure, personal SIM data.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] As of mid-2010, SIMalliance had not reported widespread industry acceptance of SCWS.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] The OMA has been maintaining the standard, approving V1.1 of the standard in May 2009, and V1.2 was expected to be approved in October 2012.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Smart cards are also used to identify user accounts on arcade machines.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Smart cards, used as transit passes, and integrated ticketing are used by many public transit operators.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Card users may also make small purchases using the cards.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Some operators offer points for usage, exchanged at retailers or for other benefits.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] However, these present a privacy risk because they allow the mass transit operator (and the government) to track an individual's movement.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] In Finland, for example, the Data Protection Ombudsman prohibited the transport operator Helsinki Metropolitan Area Council (YTV) from collecting such information, despite YTV's argument that the card owner has the right to a list of trips paid with the card.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Earlier, such information was used in the investigation of the Myyrmanni bombing.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] The UK's Department for Transport mandated smart cards to administer travel entitlements for elderly and disabled residents.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] These schemes let residents use the cards for more than just bus passes.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] They can also be used for taxi and other concessionary transport.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] One example is the "Smartcare go" scheme provided by Ecebs.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] The UK systems use the ITSO Ltd specification.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Other schemes in the UK include period travel passes, carnets of tickets or day passes and stored value which can be used to pay for journeys.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Other concessions for school pupils, students and job seekers are also supported.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] These are mostly based on the ITSO Ltd specification.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Many smart transport schemes include the use of low cost smart tickets for simple journeys, day passes and visitor passes.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] These smart tickets are made of paper or PET which is thinner than a PVC smart card e.g.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] The smart tickets can be supplied pre-printed and over-printed or printed on demand.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] In Sweden, as of 2018–19, the old SL Access smart card system has started to be phased out and replaced by smart phone apps.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] The phone apps have less cost, at least for the transit operators who don't need any electronic equipment (the riders provide that).
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] The riders are able buy tickets anywhere and don't need to load money onto smart cards.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] New NFC smart cards are still in use for foreseeable future (as of 2024).
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] In Japanese amusement arcades, contactless smart cards (usually referred to as "IC cards") are used by game manufacturers as a method for players to access in-game features (both online like Konami E-Amusement and Sega ALL.Net and offline) and as a memory support to save game progress.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Depending on a case by case scenario, the machines can use a game-specific card or a "universal" one usable on multiple machines from the same manufacturer/publisher.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Amongst the most widely used there are Banapassport by Bandai Namco, E-amusement pass by Konami, Aime by Sega and Nesica by Taito.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] In 2018, in an effort to make arcade game IC cards more user friendly, Konami, Bandai Namco and Sega have agreed on a unified system of cards named *Amusement IC*.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Thanks to this agreement, the three companies are now using a unified card reader in their arcade cabinets, so that players are able to use their card, no matter if a Banapassport, an e-Amusement Pass or an Aime, with hardware and ID services of all three manufacturers.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] A common logo for *Amusement IC* cards has been created, and this is now displayed on compatible cards from all three companies.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] In January 2019, Taito announced that their Nesica card was also joining the *Amusement IC* agreement with the other three companies.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Smart cards can be used as a security token.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Mozilla's Firefox web browser can use smart cards to store certificates for use in secure web browsing.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Some disk encryption systems, such as VeraCrypt and Microsoft's BitLocker, can use smart cards to securely hold encryption keys, and also to add another layer of encryption to critical parts of the secured disk.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] GnuPG, the well known encryption suite, also supports storing keys in a smart card.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Smart cards are also used for single sign-on to log on to computers.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Smart cards are being provided to students at some schools and colleges.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Smart cards are widely used to encrypt digital television streams.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] VideoGuard is a specific example of how smart card security worked.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] The Malaysian government promotes MyKad as a single system for all smart-card applications.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] MyKad started as identity cards carried by all citizens and resident non-citizens.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Available applications now include identity, travel documents, drivers license, health information, an electronic wallet, ATM bank-card, public toll-road and transit payments, and public key encryption infrastructure.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] The personal information inside the MYKAD card can be read using special APDU commands.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Smart cards have been advertised as suitable for personal identification tasks, because they are engineered to be tamper resistant.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] The chip usually implements some cryptographic algorithm.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] There are, however, several methods for recovering some of the algorithm's internal state.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Differential power analysis involves measuring the precise time and electric current required for certain encryption or decryption operations.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] This can deduce the on-chip private key used by public key algorithms such as RSA.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Some implementations of symmetric ciphers can be vulnerable to timing or power attacks as well.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Smart cards can be physically disassembled by using acid, abrasives, solvents, or some other technique to obtain unrestricted access to the on-board microprocessor.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Although such techniques may involve a risk of permanent damage to the chip, they permit much more detailed information (e.g., photomicrographs of encryption hardware) to be extracted.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] The primary advantage of smart cards is their flexibility.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Smart cards have multiple functions which simultaneously can be an ID, a credit card, a stored-value cash card, and a repository of personal information such as telephone numbers or medical history.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] The card can be easily replaced if lost, and, the requirement for a PIN (or other form of security) provides additional security from unauthorised access to information by others.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] At the first attempt to use it illegally, the card would be deactivated by the card reader itself.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Smart cards can be electronic key rings, giving the bearer ability to access information and physical places without need for online connections.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] They are encryption devices, so that the user can encrypt and decrypt information without relying on unknown, and therefore potentially untrustworthy, appliances such as ATMs.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Smart cards are very flexible in providing authentication at different level of the bearer and the counterpart.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Finally, with the information about the user that smart cards can provide to the other parties, they are useful devices for customizing products and services.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Smart cards can also have multiple credentials for different applications.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] This encourages better security as the user only has to manage a single card which is not only less cognitive load and more convenient.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Smart cards are easily produced and have vastly improved security allowing institutions to reduce their security spending.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Smart cards can be used in electronic commerce, over the Internet, though the business model used in current electronic commerce applications still cannot use the full feature set of the electronic medium.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] An advantage of smart cards for electronic commerce is their use customize services.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] For example, for the service supplier to deliver the customized service, the user may need to provide each supplier with their profile, a boring and time-consuming activity.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] A smart card can contain a non-encrypted profile of the bearer, so that the user can get customized services even without previous contacts with the supplier.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] The plastic or paper card in which the chip is embedded is fairly flexible.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] The larger the chip, the higher the probability that normal use could damage it.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Cards are often carried in wallets or pockets, a harsh environment for a chip and antenna in contactless cards.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] PVC cards can crack or break if bent/flexed excessively.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] However, for large banking systems, failure-management costs can be more than offset by fraud reduction.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] The production, use and disposal of PVC plastic is known to be more harmful to the environment than other plastics.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Alternative materials including chlorine free plastics and paper are available for some smart applications.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] If the account holder's computer hosts malware, the smart card security model may be broken.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Malware can override the communication (both input via keyboard and output via application screen) between the user and the application.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Man-in-the-browser malware (e.g., the Trojan Silentbanker) could modify a transaction, unnoticed by the user.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Banks like Fortis and Belfius in Belgium and Rabobank ("random reader") in the Netherlands combine a smart card with an unconnected card reader to avoid this problem.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] The customer enters a challenge received from the bank's website, a PIN and the transaction amount into the reader.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] The reader returns an 8-digit signature.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] This signature is manually entered into the personal computer and verified by the bank, preventing point-of-sale-malware from changing the transaction amount.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Smart cards have also been the targets of security attacks.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] These attacks range from physical invasion of the card's electronics, to non-invasive attacks that exploit weaknesses in the card's software or hardware.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] The usual goal is to expose private encryption keys and then read and manipulate secure data such as funds.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Once an attacker develops a non-invasive attack for a particular smart card model, he or she is typically able to perform the attack on other cards of that model in seconds, often using equipment that can be disguised as a normal smart card reader.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] While manufacturers may develop new card models with additional information security, it may be costly or inconvenient for users to upgrade vulnerable systems.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Tamper-evident and audit features in a smart card system help manage the risks of compromised cards.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] Another problem is the lack of standards for functionality and security.
[src:power-analysis-defense/smart-card-p02] To address this problem, the Berlin Group launched the ERIDANE Project to propose "a new functional and security framework for smart-card based Point of Interaction (POI) equipment".
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] Tamper resistance ranges from simple features like screws with special drives and tamper-evident seals to more complex devices that render themselves inoperable or encrypt all data transmissions between individual chips, use of materials needing special tools and knowledge.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] Tamper-resistant devices or features are common on packages to deter package or product tampering or enable its detection.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] Anti-tamper devices have one or more components: tamper resistance, tamper detection, tamper response, and tamper evidence.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] In some applications, devices are only tamper-evident rather than tamper-resistant.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] Tampering involves the deliberate altering or adulteration of a product, package, or system.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] Solutions may involve all phases of product production, packaging, distribution, logistics, sale, and use.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] No single solution can be considered as "tamper-proof".
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] Often multiple levels of security need to be addressed to reduce the risk of tampering.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] Some devices contain non-standard screws or bolts in an attempt to deter access.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] Examples are telephone switching cabinets (which have triangular bolt heads that a hex socket fits), or bolts with 5-sided heads used to secure doors to outdoor electrical distribution transformers.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] A standard Torx screw head can be made in a tamper-resistant form with a pin in the center, which excludes standard Torx drivers.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] Various other security screw heads have been devised to discourage casual access to the interior of such devices as consumer electronics.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] This style of tamper resistance is most commonly found in burglar alarms.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] Most trip devices (e.g. pressure pads, passive infrared sensors (motion detectors), door switches) use two signal wires that, depending on configuration, are normally open or normally closed.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] The sensors sometimes need power, so to simplify cable runs, multi-core cable is used.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] While 4 cores is normally enough for devices that require power (leaving two spare for those that don't), cable with additional cores can be used.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] These additional cores can be wired into a special so-called "tamper circuit" in the alarm system.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] Tamper circuits are monitored by the system to give an alarm if a disturbance to devices or wiring is detected.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] Enclosures for devices and control panels may be fitted with anti-tamper switches.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] Would-be intruders run the risk of triggering the alarm by attempting to circumvent a given device.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] Sensors such as movement detectors, tilt detectors, air-pressure sensors, light sensors, etc., which might be employed in some burglar alarms, might also be used in a bomb to hinder defusing.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] Nearly all appliances and accessories can only be opened with the use of a tool.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] This is intended to prevent casual or accidental access to energized or hot parts, or damage to the equipment.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] Manufacturers may use tamper-resistant screws, which cannot be unfastened with common tools.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] Tamper-resistant screws are used on electrical fittings in many public buildings to reduce tampering or vandalism that may cause a danger to others.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] A user who breaks equipment by modifying it in a way not intended by the manufacturer might deny they did it, in order to claim the warranty or (mainly in the case of PCs) call the helpdesk for help in fixing it.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] Tamper-evident seals may be enough to deal with this.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] However, they cannot easily be checked remotely, and many countries have statutory warranty terms that mean manufacturers may still have to service the equipment.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] Tamper proof screws will stop most casual users from tampering in the first place.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] In the US, the Magnuson-Moss Warranty Act prevents manufacturers from voiding warranties solely due to tampering.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] A warranty may be dishonored only if the tampering actually affected the part that has failed, and could have caused the failure.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] Tamper-resistant microprocessors are used to store and process private or sensitive information, such as private keys or electronic money credit.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] To prevent an attacker from retrieving or modifying the information, the chips are designed so that the information is not accessible through external means and can be accessed only by the embedded software, which should contain the appropriate security measures.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] Examples of tamper-resistant chips include all secure cryptoprocessors, such as the IBM 4758 and chips used in smartcards, as well as the Clipper chip.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] Tamper-resistant chips may be designed to zeroise their sensitive data (especially cryptographic keys) if they detect penetration of their security encapsulation or out-of-specification environmental parameters.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] A chip may even be rated for "cold zeroisation", the ability to zeroise itself even after its power supply has been crippled.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] In addition, the custom-made encapsulation methods used for chips used in some cryptographic products may be designed in such a manner that they are internally pre-stressed, so the chip will fracture if interfered with.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] Nevertheless, the fact that an attacker may have the device in their possession for as long as they like, and perhaps obtain numerous other samples for testing and practice, means that it is impossible to totally eliminate tampering by a sufficiently motivated opponent.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] Because of this, one of the most important elements in protecting a system is overall system design.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] In particular, tamper-resistant systems should "fail gracefully" by ensuring that compromise of one device does not compromise the entire system.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] In this manner, the attacker can be practically restricted to attacks that cost more than the expected return from compromising a single device.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] Since the most sophisticated attacks have been estimated to cost several hundred thousand dollars to carry out, carefully designed systems may be invulnerable in practice.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] In the United States, purchasing specifications require anti-tamper (AT) features on military electronic systems.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] Tamper resistance finds application in smart cards, set-top boxes and other devices that use digital rights management (DRM).
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] In this case, the issue is not about stopping the user from breaking the equipment or hurting themselves, but about either stopping them from extracting codes, or acquiring and saving the decoded bitstream.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] This is usually done by having many subsystem features buried within each chip (so that internal signals and states are inaccessible) and by making sure the buses between chips are encrypted.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] DRM mechanisms also use certificates and asymmetric key cryptography in many cases.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] In all such cases, tamper resistance means not allowing the device user access to the valid device certificates or public-private keys of the device.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] The process of making software robust against tampering attacks is referred to as "software anti-tamper".
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] Resistance to tampering can be built in or added to packaging.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] Software is also said to be tamper-resistant when it contains measures to make reverse engineering harder, or to prevent a user from modifying it against the manufacturer's wishes (such as removing a restriction on how it can be used).
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] One commonly used method is code obfuscation.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] However, effective tamper resistance in software is much harder than in hardware, as the software environment can be manipulated to near-arbitrary extent by the use of emulation.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] If implemented, trusted computing would make software tampering of protected programs at least as difficult as hardware tampering, as the user would have to hack the trust chip to give false certifications in order to bypass remote attestation and sealed storage.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] However, the current specification makes it clear that the chip is not expected to be tamper-proof against any reasonably sophisticated physical attack; that is, it is not intended to be as secure as a tamper-resistant device.
[src:power-analysis-defense/tamper-resistance] That has the side effect that software maintenance gets more complex because software updates need to be validated, and errors in the upgrade process may lead to a false-positive triggering of the protection mechanism.
